Your speed is determined by your race and your armor (see Table: Tactical Speed). Your speed while unarmored is your base land speed.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Encumbrance:}{\fs20\cf0  A character encumbered by carrying a large amount of gear, treasure, or fallen comrades may move slower than normal.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Hampered Movement:}{\fs20\cf0  Difficult terrain, obstacles, or poor visibility can hamper movement.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Movement in Combat:}{\fs20\cf0  Generally, you can move your speed in a round and still do something (take a move action and a standard action).
\par If you do nothing but move (that is, if you use both of your actions in a round to move your speed), you can move double your speed.
\par If you spend the entire round running, you can move quadruple your speed. If you do something that requires a full round you can only take a 5-foot step.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Bonuses to Speed:}{\fs20\cf0  A barbarian has a +10 foot bonus to his speed (unless he\rquote s wearing heavy armor). Experienced monks also have higher speed (unless they\rquote 
re wearing armor of any sort). In addition, many spells and magic items can affect a character\rquote s speed. Always apply any modifiers to a character\rquote s speed before adjusting the character\rquote 
s speed based on armor or encumbrance, and remember that multiple bonuses of the same type to a character\rquote s speed don\rquote t stack.
