\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 In melee combat, you can help a friend attack or defend by distracting or interfering with an opponent. If you\rquote 
re in position to make a melee attack on an opponent that is engaging a friend in melee combat, you can attempt to aid your friend as a standard action. You make an attack roll against AC 10. If you succeed, your friend gains either a +2 bonus on his next
 attack roll against that opponent or a +2 bonus to AC against that opponent\rquote s next attack (your choice), as long as that attack comes before the beginning of your next turn. Multiple characters can aid the same friend, and similar bonuses stack.

\par You can also use this standard action to help a friend in other ways, such as when he is affected by a spell, or to assist another character\rquote s skill check.
\par }{\cf0 
\par BULL RUSH
\par }{\fs20\cf0 You can make a bull rush as a standard action (an attack) or as part of a charge (see Charge, below
). When you make a bull rush, you attempt to push an opponent straight back instead of damaging him. You can only bull rush an opponent who is one size category larger than you, the same size, or smaller.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Initiating a Bull Rush: }{\fs20\cf0 First, you move into the defender\rquote 
s space. Doing this provokes an attack of opportunity from each opponent that threatens you, including the defender. (If you have the Improved Bull Rush feat, you don\rquote t provoke an attack of opportunity from the defender.) Any attack of opportunity 
m
ade by anyone other than the defender against you during a bull rush has a 25% chance of accidentally targeting the defender instead, and any attack of opportunity by anyone other than you against the defender likewise has a 25% chance of accidentally tar
geting you. (When someone makes an attack of opportunity, make the attack roll and then roll to see whether the attack went astray.) 
\par Second, you and the defender make opposed Strength checks. }{\fs20 You each add a +4 bonus for each size category you are larger than Medium or a \endash 
4 penalty for each size category you are smaller than Medium. You get a +2 bonus if you are charging. The defender gets a +4 bonus if he has more than two legs or is otherwise exceptionally stable.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Bull Rush Results:}{\fs20\cf0  If you beat the defender\rquote 
s Strength check result, you push him back 5 feet. If you wish to move with the defender, you can push him back an additional 5 feet for each 5 points by which your check result is greater than the defender\rquote s check result. You can\rquote 
t, however, exceed your normal movement limit. (}{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 The defender provokes attacks of opportunity if he is moved. So do you, if you move with him. The two of you do not provoke attacks of opportunity from each other, however.)

\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 If you fail to beat the defender\rquote s Strength check r
esult, you move 5 feet straight back to where you were before you moved into his space. If that space is occupied, you fall prone in that space.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cf0 
\par CHARGE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Charging is a special full-round action that allows you to move up to twice your speed and attack during the action. However, it carries tight restrictions on how you can move.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Movement During a Charge:}{\fs20\cf0  You must move before your attack, not after. You must move at least 10 feet (2 squares) and may move up to double your speed directly toward the designated opponent.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 
You must have a clear path toward the opponent, and nothing can hinder your movement (such as difficult terrain or obstacles). Here\rquote s what it means to have a clear path. First, you must mov
e to the closest space from which you can attack the opponent. (If this space is occupied or otherwise blocked, you can\rquote 
t charge.) Second, if any line from your starting space to the ending space passes through a square that blocks movement, slows movement, or contains a creature (even an ally), you can\rquote t charge. (Helpless creatures don\rquote t stop a charge.)

\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 If you don\rquote t have line of sight to the opponent at the start of your turn, you can\rquote t charge that opponent.

\par You can\rquote t take a 5-foot step in the same round as a charge.
\par If you are able to take only a standard action or a move action on your turn, you can still charge, but you are only allowed to move up to your speed (instead of up to double your speed). You can\rquote t use this option unless you are restricted to t
aking only a standard action or move action on your turn.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attacking on a Charge:}{\fs20\cf0  After moving, you may make a single melee attack. You get a +2 bonus on the attack roll. and take a \endash 2 penalty to your AC until the start of your next turn.
\par A charging character gets a +2 bonus on the Strength check made to bull rush an opponent (see Bull Rush, above).
\par Even if you have extra attacks, such as from having a high enough base attack bonus or from using multiple weapons, you only get to make one attack during a charge.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Lances and Charge Attacks:}{\fs20\cf0  A lance deals double damage if employed by a mounted character in a charge.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Weapons Readied against a Charge: }{\fs20\cf0 Spears, tridents, and certain other piercing weapons deal double damage when readied (set) and used against a charging character.
\par }{\cf0 
\par DISARM
\par }{\fs20\cf0 As a melee attack, you may attempt to disarm your opponent. If you do so with a weapon, you knock the opponent\rquote s weapon out of his hands and to the ground. If you attempt the disarm while unarmed, you e
nd up with the weapon in your hand.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 If you\rquote 
re attempting to disarm a melee weapon, follow the steps outlined here. If the item you are attempting to disarm isn\rquote t a melee weapon the defender may still oppose you with an attack roll, but takes a penalty and can\rquote 
t attempt to disarm you in return if your attempt fails.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Step 1:}{\fs20\cf0 
 Attack of Opportunity. You provoke an attack of opportunity from the target you are trying to disarm. (If you have the Improved Disarm feat, you don\rquote t incur an attack of opportunity for making a disarm attempt.) If the defender\rquote 
s attack of opportunity deals any damage, your disarm attempt fails.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 2:}{\fs20\cf0  Opposed Rolls. You and the defender make opposed attack rolls with your respective weapons. The wielder of a two-handed weapon on a disarm attempt gets a +4 bonus on this roll, and the wielder of a light weapon takes a 
\endash 4 penalty. (An unarmed strike is considered a light weapon, so you always take a penalty when trying to disarm an opponent by using an unarmed strike.) If the combatants are 
of different sizes, the larger combatant gets a bonus on the attack roll of +4 per difference in size category. If the targeted item isn\rquote t a melee weapon, the defender takes a \endash 4 penalty on the roll.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step Three:}{\fs20\cf0  Consequences. If you beat the defender, the defender is disarmed. If you attempted the disarm action unarmed, you now have the weapon. If you were armed, the defender\rquote s weapon is on the ground in the defender
\rquote s square.
\par If you fail on the disarm attempt, the defender may immediately react and attempt
 to disarm you with the same sort of opposed melee attack roll. His attempt does not provoke an attack of opportunity from you. If he fails his disarm attempt, you do not subsequently get a free disarm attempt against him.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 A defender wearing spiked gauntlets can\rquote t be disarmed. A defender using a weapon attached to a locked gauntlet gets a +10 bonus to resist being disarmed.
\par 
\par Grabbing Items
\par You can use a disarm action to snatch an item worn by the target. If you want to have the item in your hand, the disarm must be made as an unarmed attack.
\par If the item is poorly secured or otherwise easy to snatch or cut away the attacker gets a +4 bonus. Unlike on a normal disarm attempt, failing the attempt doesn\rquote t allow the defender to attempt to disarm you. This o
therwise functions identically to a disarm attempt, as noted above.
\par You can\rquote t snatch an item that is well secured unless you have pinned the wearer (see Grapple). Even then, the defender gains a +4 bonus on his roll to resist the attempt.
\par }{\cf0 
\par FEINT
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Feinting is a standard action. To feint, make a Bluff check opposed by a Sense Motive check by your target. The target may add his base attack bonus to this Sense Motive check. If your Bluff check result exceeds your target\rquote 
s Sense Motive check result, the next melee attack you make against the target does not allow him to use his Dexterity bonus to AC (if any). This attack must be made on or before your next turn.
\par When feinting in this way against a nonhumanoid you take a \endash 4 penalty. Against a creature of animal Intelligence (1 or 2), you take a \endash 8 penalty. Against a nonintelligent creature, it\rquote s impossible.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 Feinting in combat does not provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Feinting as a Move Action:}{\fs20\cf0  With the Improved Feint feat, you can attempt a feint as a move action ins
tead of as a standard action.
\par }{\cf0 
\par GRAPPLE
\par }{\fs20\cf0 
\par Grapple Checks
\par Repeatedly in a grapple, you need to make opposed grapple checks against an opponent. A grapple check is like a melee attack roll. Your attack bonus on a grapple check is: Base attack bonus + Strength modifier + special size modifier
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special Size Modifier:}{\fs20\cf0  The special size modifier for a grapple check is as follows: Colossal +16, Gargantuan +12, Huge +8, Large +4, Medium +0, Small \endash 4, Tiny \endash 8, Diminutive \endash 12, Fine \endash 16. Use this 
number in place of the normal size modifier you use when making an attack roll.
\par 
\par Starting a Grapple
\par To start a grapple, you need to grab and hold your target. Starting a grapple requires a successful melee attack roll. If you get multiple attacks, you can attempt to start a grapple multiple times (at successively lower base attack bonuses).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 1:}{\fs20\cf0  Attack of Opportunity. You provoke an attack of opportunity from the target you are trying to grapple. If the attack of opportunity deals damage, the grapple att
empt fails. (Certain monsters do not provoke attacks of opportunity when they attempt to grapple, nor do characters with the Improved Grapple feat.) If the attack of opportunity misses or fails to deal damage, proceed to Step 2.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 2:}{\fs20\cf0  Grab. You make a melee touch attack to grab the target. If you fail to hit the target, the grapple attempt fails. If you succeed, proceed to Step 3.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 3:}{\fs20\cf0  Hold. Make an opposed grapple check as a free action.
\par If you succeed, you and your target are now grappling, and you deal damage to the target as if with an unarmed strike.
\par If you lose, you fail to start the grapple. You automatically lose an attempt to hold if the target is two or more size categories larger than you are.
\par In case of a tie, the combatant with the higher grapple check modifier wins. If this is a tie, roll again to break the tie.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 4:}{\fs20\cf0  Maintain Grapple. To maintain the grapple for later rounds, you must move into the target\rquote s space. (This movement is free and doesn\rquote t count as part of your movement in the round.)
\par Moving, as normal, provokes attacks of opportunity from threatening opponents, but not from your target.
\par If you can\rquote t move into your target\rquote s space, you can\rquote t maintain the grapple and must immediately let go of the target. To grapple again, you must begin at Step 1.
\par 
\par Grappling Consequences
\par While you\rquote re grappling, your ability to attack others and defend yourself is limited.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 No Threatened Squares:}{\fs20\cf0  You don\rquote t threaten any squares while grappling.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 No Dexterity Bonus:}{\fs20\cf0  You lose your Dexterity bonus to AC (if you have one) against opponents you aren\rquote t grappling. (You can still use it against opponents you are grappling.)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 No Movement:}{\fs20\cf0  You can\rquote t move normally while grappling. You may, however, make an opposed grapple check (see below) to move while grappling.
\par 
\par If You\rquote re Grappling
\par When you are grappling (regardless of who started the grapple), you can perform any of the following actions. Some of these actions take the place of an attack (rather than being a standard action or a move action).
 If your base attack bonus allows you multiple attacks, you can attempt one of these actions in place of each of your attacks, but at successively lower base attack bonuses.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Activate a Magic Item:}{\fs20\cf0  You can activate a magic item, as long as the item doesn\rquote t require a spell completion trigger. You don\rquote t need to make a grapple check to activate the item.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Attack Your Opponent:}{\fs20\cf0  You can make an attack with an unarmed strike, natural weapon, or light weapon against another character you are grappling. You take a \endash 4 penalty on such attacks.
\par You can\rquote t attack with two weapons while grappling, even if both are light weapons.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Cast a Spell:}{\fs20\cf0  You can attempt to cast a spell while grappling or even while pinned (see below), provide
d its casting time is no more than 1 standard action, it has no somatic component, and you have in hand any material components or focuses you might need. Any spell that requires precise and careful action}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 
is impossible to cast while grappling or being pinned. If the spell is one that you can cast while grappling, you must make a Concentration check (DC 20 + spell level) or lose the spell. You don\rquote 
t have to make a successful grapple check to cast the spell.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Damage Your Opponent:}{\fs20\cf0  While grappling, you can dea
l damage to your opponent equivalent to an unarmed strike. Make an opposed grapple check in place of an attack. If you win, you deal nonlethal damage as normal for your unarmed strike (1d3 points for Medium attackers or 1d2 points for Small attackers, plu
s Strength modifiers). If you want to deal lethal damage, you take a \endash 4 penalty on your grapple check.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Exception: }{\fs20\cf0 Monks deal more damage on an unarmed strike than other characters, and the damage is lethal. However, they can choose to deal their damage as nonlethal damage when grappling without taking the usual \endash 
4 penalty for changing lethal damage to nonlethal damage.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Draw a Light Weapon:}{\fs20\cf0  You can draw a light weapon as a move action with a successful grapple check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Escape from Grapple:}{\fs20\cf0  You can escape a grap
ple by winning an opposed grapple check in place of making an attack. You can make an Escape Artist check in place of your grapple check if you so desire, but this requires a standard action. If more than one opponent is grappling you, your grapple check 
result has to beat all their individual check results to escape. (Opponents don\rquote t have to try to hold you if they don\rquote t want to.) If you escape, you finish the action by moving into any space adjacent to your opponent(s).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Move:}{\fs20\cf0  You can move half your speed 
(bringing all others engaged in the grapple with you) by winning an opposed grapple check. This requires a standard action, and you must beat all the other individual check results to move the grapple.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 You get a +4 bonus on your grapple check to move a pinned opponent, but only if no one else is involved in the grapple.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Retrieve a Spell Component: }{\fs20\cf0 You can produce a spell component from your pouch while grappling by using a full-round action. Doing so does not require a successful grapple check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Pin Your Opponent:}{\fs20\cf0  You can hold your opponent immobile for 1 round by winning an opposed grapple check (made in place of an attack). Once you have an opponent pinned, you have a few options available to you (see below).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Break Another\rquote s Pin: }{\fs20\cf0 If you are grappling 
an opponent who has another character pinned, you can make an opposed grapple check in place of an attack. If you win, you break the hold that the opponent has over the other character. The character is still grappling, but is no longer pinned.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Use Opponent\rquote s Weapon: }{\fs20\cf0 If your opponent is holding a light weapon, you can use it to attack him. Make an opposed grapple check (in place of an attack). If you win, make an attack roll with the weapon with a \endash 
4 penalty (doing this doesn\rquote t require another action).
\par You don\rquote t gain possession of the weapon by performing this action.
\par 
\par If You\rquote re Pinning an Opponent
\par You can attempt to damage your opponent with an opposed grapple check, you can attempt to use your opponent\rquote s weapon against him, or you can attempt to move the g
rapple (all described above). At your option, you can prevent a pinned opponent from speaking.
\par You can use a disarm action to remove or grab away a well secured object worn by a pinned opponent, but he gets a +4 bonus on his roll to resist your attempt (see Disarm).
\par You may voluntarily release a pinned character as a free action; if you do so, you are no longer considered to be grappling that character (and vice versa).
\par You can\rquote t draw or use a weapon (against the pinned character or any other character), escape another\rquote s grapple, retrieve a spell component, pin another character, or break another\rquote s pin while you are pinning an opponent.
\par 
\par If You\rquote re Pinned by an Opponent
\par When an opponent has pinned you, you are held immobile (but not helpless) for 1 round. While you\rquote re pinned, you take a \endash 4 penalty to your AC against opponents other than the one pinning you. At your opponent\rquote 
s option, you may also be unable to speak. On your turn, you can try to escape the pin by making an opposed grapple check in place of an a
ttack. You can make an Escape Artist check in place of your grapple check if you want, but this requires a standard action. If you win, you escape the pin, but you\rquote re still grappling.
\par 
\par Joining a Grapple
\par If your target is already grappling someone else, you can use an attack to start a grapple, as above, except that the target doesn\rquote 
t get an attack of opportunity against you, and your grab automatically succeeds. You still have to make a successful opposed grapple check to become part of the grapple.
\par If there are multiple opponents involved in the grapple, you pick one to make the opposed grapple check against.
\par 
\par Multiple Grapplers
\par Several combatants can be in a single grapple. Up to four combatants can grapple a single opponent in a given round. Creatures tha
t are one or more size categories smaller than you count for half, creatures that are one size category larger than you count double, and creatures two or more size categories larger count quadruple.
\par When you are grappling with multiple opponents, you choose one opponent to make an opposed check against. The exception is an attempt to escape from the grapple; to successfully escape, your grapple check must beat the check results of each opponent.

