\par MOUNTED COMBAT
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Horses in Combat: }{\fs20\cf0 Warhorses and warponies can serve readily as combat steeds. Light horses, ponies, and heavy horses, however, are frightened by combat. If you don\rquote 
t dismount, you must make a DC 20 Ride check each round as a move action to control such a horse. If you succeed, you can perform a standard action after the move action. If you fail, the move action becomes a full round action and you can\rquote 
t do anything else until your next turn.
\par Your mount acts on your initiative count as you direct it. You move at its speed, but the mount uses its action to move.
\par A horse (not a pony) is a Large creature and thus takes up a space 10 feet (2 squares) across. For simplicity, assume that you share your mount\rquote s space during combat.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Combat while Mounted:}{\fs20\cf0  With a DC 5 Ride check, you can guide your mount with your knees so as to use both hands to attack or defend yourself. This is a free action.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 When you attack a creature smaller than your mount that is on foot, you get the +1 bonus on melee attacks for being 
on higher ground. If your mount moves more than 5 feet, you can only make a single melee attack. Essentially, you have to wait until the mount gets to your enemy before attacking, so you can\rquote t make a full attack. Even at your mount\rquote 
s full speed, you don\rquote t take any penalty on melee attacks while mounted.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
If your mount charges, you also take the AC penalty associated with a charge. If you make an attack at the end of the charge, you receive the bonus gained from the charge. When charging on horseback, you deal double damage with a lance (see Charge).

\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 You can use ranged weapons while your mount is taking a double move, but at a \endash 
4 penalty on the attack roll. You can use ranged weapons while your mount is running (quadruple speed), at a \endash 8 penalty. In either cas
e, you make the attack roll when your mount has completed half its movement. You can make a full attack with a ranged weapon while your mount is moving. Likewise, you can take move actions normally
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Spells while Mounted:}{\fs20\cf0  You can cast a spell normall
y if your mount moves up to a normal move (its speed) either before or after you cast. If you have your mount move both before and after you cast a spell, then you\rquote 
re casting the spell while the mount is moving, and you have to make a Concentration check d
ue to the vigorous motion (DC 10 + spell level) or lose the spell. If the mount is running (quadruple speed), you can cast a spell when your mount has moved up to twice its speed, but your Concentration check is more difficult due to the violent motion (D
C 15 + spell level).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 If Your Mount Falls in Battle:}{\fs20\cf0  If your mount falls, you have to succeed on a DC 15 Ride check to make a soft fall and take no damage. If the check fails, you take 1d6 points of damage.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 If You Are Dropped:}{\fs20\cf0  If you are knocked unconscious, you have a 50% chance to stay in the saddle (or 75% if you\rquote re in a military saddle). Otherwise you fall and take 1d6 points of damage.
\par Without you to guide it, your mount avoids combat.
\par }{\cf0 
\par OVERRUN
\par }{\fs20\cf0 You can attempt an overrun as a standard action taken during your move
. (In general, you cannot take a standard action during a move; this is an exception.) With an overrun, you attempt to plow past or over your opponent (and move through his square) as you move. You can only overrun an oppo
nent who is one size category larger than you, the same size, or smaller. You can make only one overrun attempt per round.
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 If you\rquote re attempting to overrun an opponent, follow these steps.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Step 1:}{\fs20\cf0  Attack of Opportunity. Since you begin the overrun by moving into the defender\rquote 
s space, you provoke an attack of opportunity from the defender.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 2: }{\fs20\cf0 Opponent Avoids? The defender has the option to simply avoid you. If he avoids you, he doesn\rquote t suffer any ill effect and you may keep moving
 (You can always move through a square occupied by someone who lets you by.) The overrun attempt doesn\rquote t count against your actions this round (except for any movement required to enter the opponent\rquote s square). If your opponent doesn\rquote 
t avoid you, move to Step 3.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 3:}{\fs20\cf0  Opponent Blocks? If your opponent blocks you, make a Strength check opposed by the defender\rquote s Dexterity or Strength check (whichever ability score has the higher modifier). A combatant gets a +4 b
onus on the check for every size category he is larger than Medium or a \endash 4 penalty for every size category he is smaller than Medium. The defender gets a +4 bonus on hi
s check if he has more than two legs or is otherwise more stable than a normal humanoid. If you win, you knock the defender prone. If you lose, the defender may immediately react and make a Strength check opposed by your Dexterity or Strength check (inclu
ding the size modifiers noted above, but no other modifiers) to try to knock you prone.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Step 4: }{\fs20\cf0 Consequences. If you succeed in knocking your opponent prone, you can continue your movement as normal. If you fail and are knocked prone in turn, you have to mo
ve 5 feet back the way you came and fall prone, ending your movement there. If you fail but are not knocked prone, you have to move 5 feet back the way you came, ending your movement there. If that square is occupied, you fall prone in that square.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Improved Overrun:}{\fs20\cf0  If you have the Improved Overrun feat, your target may not choose to avoid you.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Mounted Overrun (Trample):}{\fs20\cf0  If you attempt an overrun while mounted, your mount makes the Strength check to determine the success or failure of the overrun attack (an
d applies its size modifier, rather than yours). If you have the Trample feat and attempt an overrun while mounted, your target may not choose to avoid you, and if you knock your opponent prone with the overrun, your mount may make one hoof attack against
 your opponent.
