\par TURN OR REBUKE UNDEAD
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Good clerics and paladins and some neutral clerics can channel positive energy, which can halt, drive off (rout), or destroy undead.
\par Evil clerics and some neutral clerics can channel negative energy, which can halt, awe (rebuke), control (command), or bolster undead.
\par Regardless of the effect, the general term for the activity is \'93turning.\'94 When attempting to exercise their divine control over these creatures, characters make turning checks.
\par 
\par Turning Checks
\par Turning undead is a supernatural ability that a character can perform as a standard action. It does not provoke attacks of opportunity.
\par You must present your holy symbol to turn undead. Turning is considered an attack.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Times per Day: }{\fs20\cf0 You may attempt to turn undead a number of times per day equal to 3 + your Charisma modifier. You can increase this number by taking the Extra Turning feat.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range:}{\fs20\cf0  You turn the closest turnable undead first, and you can\rquote t turn undead that are more than 60 feet away or that have total cover relative to you. You don\rquote t need line of sight to a target, but 
you do need line of effect.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Turning Check:}{\fs20\cf0  The first thing you do is roll a turning check to see how powerful an undead creature you can turn. This is a Charisma check (1d20 + your Charisma modifier). Table: Turning Undead gives you the Hit Dice of the mos
t powerful undead you can affect, relative to your level. On a given turning attempt, you can turn no undead creature whose Hit Dice exceed the result on this table.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Turning Damage:}{\fs20\cf0  If your roll on Table: Turning Undead is high enough to let you turn at least some of the undead within 60 feet, roll 2d6 + your cleric level + your Charisma modifier for turning damage. That\rquote 
s how many total Hit Dice of undead you can turn.
\par If your Charisma score is average or low, it\rquote s possible to roll fewer Hit Dice of undead turned than indicated on Table: Turning Undead.
\par You may skip over already turned undead that are still within range, so that you do not waste your turning capacity on them.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Effect and Duration of Turning:}{\fs20\cf0 
 Turned undead flee from you by the best and fastest means available to them. They flee for 10 rounds (1 minute). If they cannot flee, they cower (giving any attack rolls against them a +2 bonus). If you approach within 10 feet of t
hem, however, they overcome being turned and act normally. (You can stand within 10 feet without breaking the turning effect\emdash you just can\rquote 
t approach them.) You can attack them with ranged attacks (from at least 10 feet away), and others can attack them in any fashion, without breaking the turning effect.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Destroying Undead:}{\fs20\cf0  If you have twice as many levels (or more) as the undead have Hit Dice, you destroy any that you would normally turn.
