\par SPECIAL INITIATIVE ACTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Here are ways to change when you act during combat by altering your place in the initiative order.
\par }{\cf0 
\par DELAY
\par }{\fs20\cf0 By choosing to delay, you take no action and then act normally on whatever initiative count you decide to act. When you delay, you voluntarily reduce 
your own initiative result for the rest of the combat. When your new, lower initiative count comes up later in the same round, you can act normally. You can specify this new initiative result or just wait until some time later in the round and act then, t
hus fixing your new initiative count at that point.
\par You never get back the time you spend waiting to see what\rquote s going to happen. You can\rquote t, however, interrupt anyone else\rquote s action (as you can with a readied action).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Initiative Consequences of Delaying: }{\fs20\cf0 Your initiative result becomes the count on which you took the delayed action. If you come to your next action and have not yet performed an action, you don\rquote 
t get to take a delayed action (though you can delay again).
\par If you take a delayed action in the next round, before your regular turn comes up, your initiative count rises to that new point in the order of battle, and you do not get your regular action that round.
\par }{\cf0 
\par READY
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The ready action lets you prepare to take an action later, after your turn is over but before your next one has begun. Readying is a standard action. It does not provoke an attack of opportunity (though the action that you ready might do so).

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Readying an Action:}{\fs20\cf0  You can ready a standard action, a move action, or a free action. To do so, 
specify the action you will take and the conditions under which you will take it. Then, any time before your next action, you may take the readied action in response to that condition. The action occurs just before the action that triggers it. If the trig
gered action is part of another character\rquote 
s activities, you interrupt the other character. Assuming he is still capable of doing so, he continues his actions once you complete your readied action. Your initiative result changes. For the rest of the encounte
r, your initiative result is the count on which you took the readied action, and you act immediately ahead of the character whose action triggered your readied action.
\par You can take a 5-foot step as part of your readied action, but only if you don\rquote t otherwise move any distance during the round. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Initiative Consequences of Readying:}{\fs20\cf0  Your initiative result becomes the count on which you took the readied action. If you come to your next action and have not yet performed your readied action, you don\rquote t get to tak
e the readied action (though you can ready the same action again). If you take your readied action in the next round, before your regular turn comes up, your initiative count rises to that new point in the order of battle, and you do not get your regular 
action that round.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Distracting Spellcasters:}{\fs20\cf0  You can ready an attack against a spellcaster with the trigger \'93if she starts casting a spell.\'94
 If you damage the spellcaster, she may lose the spell she was trying to cast (as determined by her Concentration check result).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Readying to Counterspell:}{\fs20\cf0  You may ready a counterspell against a spellcaster (often with the trigger \'93if she starts casting a spell\'94
). In this case, when the spellcaster starts a spell, you get a chance to identify it with a Spellcraft check (D
C 15 + spell level). If you do, and if you can cast that same spell (are able to cast it and have it prepared, if you prepare spells), you can cast the spell as a counterspell and automatically ruin the other spellcaster\rquote 
s spell. Counterspelling works even if one spell is divine and the other arcane.
\par A spellcaster can use }{\i\fs20\cf0 dispel magic }{\fs20\cf0 to counterspell another spellcaster, but it doesn\rquote t always work.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Readying a Weapon against a Charge:}{\fs20\cf0  You can ready certain piercing weapons, setting them to receive charges. A readied weapon of this type deals double damage if you score a hit with it against a charging character.
